<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="131" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[168,775,643,840]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,643,667]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Identification.</emphasis>
Its carapace is highly flexible, with 11–13 moveable bands. Hair is sparse. The body is dark brown, except for the head and tail and for a light-colored stripe around the edges of the body. The tail is long, narrow, and covered with small pentagonal scales (
<bibRefCitation author="Carter TS &amp; Superina M &amp; Leslie DMJ" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" pagination="21 - 34" refId="ref6604" refString="Carter TS, Superina M, Leslie DMJ (2016) Priodontes maximus (Cingulata: Chlamyphoridae). Mammalian Species 48 (932): 21 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / mspecies / sew 002" type="journal article" year="2016">Carter et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
